{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00222254711/1930072601/0911.xml":{"full_text":"v&3> dsZ' \u25a0sgg\nMEWSah_d\"MS\n/6UILOING LOAN\nIM SOON\nTO MEET\nAnnual Convention to Draw\n1,200 Members Next Week,\nDirector Announces Here\n\nTwelve hundred members of\nK the \u2022U. S.z Building and Loan\nj League, founded in 1893, will\nconvene in Grand Rapids. Mich.,\n\u2019on July 29, for their thirty-eighth\nannual convention, it was made\nII known here yesterday by C. Clin-\nton James, director of the league,\nS' who will preside over the meet-\nIng of the executive officers\u2019 di-\nvision.\nCarl H. Weber, Springfield. 111.,\npresident of the National Asso\nelation of Building and Loan\nSupervisors, will preside at the\n\u25a0meetings of the building and\n\u25a0loan officials and State super\n\u00aevisors, and George L. Bliss. New\ncity, president of the\n\u25a0American Savings Building and\n\u25a0Loan Institute, will open the\n\u25a0round-table discussions of this\n\u25a0organization, which is the edu\n\u25a0cational research part of the\n||S Many Speakers Listed\nSpeakers listed for the three-\nday session will discuss real es-;\nMs tate appraisal, State supervision,\nthe trend in real estate values,\nthe outlook for home ownership,\nadvanced accounting systems, the;\nmerits of financial advertising.\nV the educational courses provided\nF through the American Savings\nBuilding and Loan Institute, the\nimportance of State legislation.\nand the advantages of stronger\norganization on the part of those\nengaged in this business.\nGroup conferences and round\ntable discussions es attorneys\nparticipating in building and loan\nwork. State supervisors under\nwhose direction building and loan\norganizations are operated, ad-'\nVertising experts and other spe-)\ncialists, will be held during the\nconvention period.\nPresided over by Ernest A.\nI Bale, president, Suffolk Co-Opera\ntive Bank. Boston, president of\nthe league, the convention will\nopen next Tuesday morning after;\nI the meeting of the directors and\nthe executive committee the pre\nVloUm day.\nThe, feature of the Tuesday\nmommg program is 'Thomas F.\nHolden, vice ptesident of the F.\nW. Dodge Corporation, New York\ncity, who, speaking on \u201cThe Real\nI Estate and Business Outlook.\u201d\nwill give the building and loan\nmen a pictyre of what to expect\nduring the next year from the\n|L point of ..view of the Dodge Cor-\nporation, long engaged in build-\ning and financial analysis.\nCure for Depression\nAlong the sime subject lines\nV Is the address of the other head\nliner, James S. Natthews, of the\n\u25a0k Babson Institute, who will speak\non \u201cThe Way Out of Our Busi-\nness Depression.\u201d He will not\nconfine himself to the building\nB and loan business.\n\u201cWhither Home Ownership\u201d is\nthe terse title listed for Leonard\nS P. Reaumo, president of the Na-\ntional Association of Real Estate\nBoards, who is expected to face\nthe issue of apartment life en-\ncroachment on thejiome idea.\nHome ownership will also be the\nK theme of ex-Gov. Chase Osborne,\nof Michigan, who will address the\ngeneral sessions on Thursday, the\nlast diy of the meeting.\nThis is the first convention of\nL this organization held under the\nnew national set-up which pic-\nF vided for a Chicago headquarters,\nF and an executive manager, who is\nH. Morton Bodfish, formerly with\nB the National Association of Real\nEstate. Boards. This new set-up\nprovides for increasing the assets\nof league members and knitting\nB together even more closely the\nB men. and women engaged in this\nbusiness.\nDiscarded Cruisers\nAre Up For Auction\nH Two of the Navy\u2019s obsolete\nU cruisers, the U. S. S. lunting-\nS ton and St. Louis, will be sold\nunder sealed bids to be opened at\n11 a. m. August 7, the Navy De-\nF-' partment announced yesterday.\nThe ships are offered for sale\nB on the condition that certain\nArmor plates 'be removed from\nthem and returned to the Gov-\nF eminent'\nI HERALD\nHARBOR\n(On the Severn)\nDo not fail to see our\nspecial list of choice lots\nfor a limited\npe\u00dfod at one-half price.\nIn celebration of the new\nr State road to the en\ntrance of property\u2014save\n50%.\nAgents on Property Daily\nt Shelton Cotton, Inc.\nExclusive Agents\nr <l9* A Southern Building\nNational 2621\nFort Bayard Park Homes\niisii i i ii hi .i muJ\njfIHM\nW f HHwi US jm pH MBS\nOUmCk JSII a HBIIB Ml Ml B j'\nI\nVMR S\u2019 -WflW\ni K -Mi\nJHH\n-1 j\nB\u2019\nW\nFiyE EARLY AMERICAN TYPE homes recently completed by Boss and Phelps\nin their new Fort Bayard Park development. These homes are located at Forty\nfourth Street and Brandywine. Lower view shows rear of houses with detached\ngarage.\nCOOLET HOUSES\nSELLING EAST\n\nThe sale of four of the nine\nI early American English type\nhomes, recently completed, on T\nStreet, between Thirty-eighth and\nThirty-ninth streets, by Cooley\nBrothers, is indicative of the\nstrong demand for this attractive\ntype of row dwelling, and accord\ning to the builders, work will start\nat once on eight more, which will\nmake a row of 17 houses.\nLocated in Burleith Heights, and\n\u2022constructed of the best possible\nbuilding materials, these homes,\nranging in size from six to eight\nrooms, with one and two baths,\nrange in price from SIO,OOO to\n$14,000. Each lot is 172 feet deep\nwith detached brick garage. Paved\nalleys and streets, shrubs, trees\nand additional features afford\neach home an ideal setting.\nEach home is modemistically\ndecorated throughout, while an\nopen fireplace in the living room\nmakes this the showroom of the\nhouse. Hardwood floors, cedar\nlined closets, frigidaire, slate gable\nroof, bright basements with laun\ndry trays, new type furnace and\nPittsburgh instantaneous water\nheater add much to the comforts\nof the home.\nA concrete front porch and two\nscreened-in rear porches afford ad\nditional space. Located on a high\nelevation and with a southern ex\nposure, these homes offer comfort\nio home owners who find it neces\nsary to\u2019;remain in Washington\nduring the summer months.\n165 Md. Properties\nListed in Tax Sales\nLEONARDTOWN, Md., July 26.\nOnly 165 pieces of property are\nadvertised by Mrs. Charlotte B.\nFowler, county treasurer, this\nweek in the sale for 1928-1929\ntaxes.\nLast year nearly 300 proper\nties were advertised, records show.\nONLY ONE OF THESE\nI At $2,000 Less Than Regular Price\nYou Can Buy This Home for the Rent You j\nAre Now Paying. Why Not Come Out? 1\nSIOO CASH I\nBalance $75 Monthly, Including Interest j\n765 Princeton St. N. W.\nJUST EAST OF GA. AVE. N. W. S\ni;\n8 Rooms and Bath\u2014Hot-water Heat\nElectric Lights\u2014Big Porches r\nVery Large Lots to Wide Alley\ni _ Fine Built-in Garage J J\nInspect Today [a\nOpen, and Lighted Until 9 O\u2019Clock P. y I\nitLRJ-fo WERSTEIN g|\n1311 H STREET NORTHWEST i\"\nTelephone District 5260\nMGHITECTS TO\nKEEP RECORDS\nPlans for the creation of Pic\ntoral Archives at the Library of\nCongress to aid in the preserva\ntion of a national record of early\nAmerican architecture are rapidly\nbeing developed, according to the\nAmerican Institute of Architects.\nThe Institute is seeking co-opera\ntion in building up the collection\nand the report stated that more\nthan 5,000 negatives have already\nbeen received or promised.\nA grant from the Carnegie Cor\nporation has enabled the prints\nreceived to be catalogued and an\nextensive booklet is being pre\npared of illustrative material\nwhich has appeared in books and\nmagazines.\nThe report, prepared for the\ninstitute by Leicester B. Holland,\nchief of the division of fine arts\nof the Library of Congress, said\nno effort has been made to record\non a national scale the material\naspect of our past and that the\ncreation of this new division will\ncreate a repository where photo\ngraphic records from the whole\nUnited States may be assembled.\nThe Library of Congress ap\nparently is the only national in\nstitution which can logically un\ndertake this work, and a sub\ndivision of fine arts is being\nestablished to serve as national\nPictoral Archives of Early Ameri\ncan Architecture.\nIn all probability the archives\nwill consist of three parts; a col\nlection of negatives, all-embrac\ning as possible: complete folio\nfiles of prints from these nega\ntives, for consultation; and very\nfull indices, toppgraphics, chrono\nlogic and by subject, so that de\nsired matter may be readily lo\ncated.\nNegatives of all sizes and from\nall sections of the country will\nbe welcome. All negatives will\ni?e carefully indexed, with the\nname of the photographer and\ndonor permanently recorded.\nWASIffIMSSRWE S\nShainwald to Fight\nFor Sister\u2019s Estate\nNEW YORK, July 26 (U.S.).\nRalph L. Shainwald served notice\nin surrogate's court here that\nhe will contest the will of his sis\nter, Marion, whereby her $700,000\nproperty goes to her husband, Col.\nGranville Sevier, now stationed\nat Fort Shafter, Honolulu.\nMrs. Sevier, who married the\ncoloned in 1925, died in the Ha\nwaiian Islands in August, 1928.\nShortly afterward her brother\nasked an investigation into the\ncauses of her death.\nShainwald charges his sister\nwas of unsound mind. He asks a\njury trial.\nBest Buys in N. E. Priced Under SB,OOO\nInspect at Once\n1601 to 1619\nD St. N. E.\n5 SOLD\nThe architecture of these\nfine homes has been care\nfully designed and selected\nby our experts of superior\nhome designs. The ma\nterial also has been care\nfully selected. All labor\nfurnished by skilled me\nchanics of the best grade.\nThese homes contain six,\nseven and eight large\nrooms, tile bath and built\nin tub and shower, one\npiece sink in kitchen, extra\nlarge porches front and\nrear. Oak floors, latest\nfixtures; floor plugs tn\neach room and lots of\nextras. Built by White\nUnion Labor.\nFrigidaire and Garage\nWith Each House\nFor Sale by\nTHOS. A. JAMESON CO.\n906 New York Avenue National 5526\nSATURDAY, JULY 26, 1930\n(Mbire\nJlWar\u00dfarvartr\n\u2022ately Priced I\nJO Apartments in a\nmost favorable Hk\nlocation. Ideal Pfe\nfor Apartment fcOP\nResidence at any I\nseason. J\nc\nt 4 J I\nEvery apartment at the Chalfonte is an outside'apartment\nwith a garden outlook. Cool breezes from the verdant stretches\nof Rock Creek park assure those living at the Chalfonte per*\nfeet comfort during warm months of summer and early fall.\nThe Chalfonte is thoroughly modem and has been designed\nwith especially large rooms having ample closet space. Most\napartments have spacious screened sleeping porches.\nR.ntalt From $45.00 Por Month\nL B. ZIMMER. Manager Adams \u00bb710\nOffice Addreea, 1317-21 B St N. W.\nBOSS PHELPS\nEXHIBITNEW\nHOME\nAnswering the appeal of the\nfamily of medium Income for a\ncomfortable home at a moderate\ncoat. Bosa and Phelps, local real\ntors and developers of Foxhall\nVillage, announced yesterday the\nopening of another exhibit home\nat 4615 Forty-fourth St., In their\nnew Fort Bayard Park section.\nThe two-story, basement and\nattic house is designed along the\nlines of architecture embodied in\nthe early American home, and is\nof high-grade construction. The\nhall, living room, dining room,\nkitchen and breakfast room on\nthe first floor, with the three\nbedrooms and bath comprising\nthe second floor, have been fin\nished and decorated throughout\nand present the acme of home\ncomfort and \u201cUvingness.\u201d\nInteresting Features\nDesigned to meet the require\nments of the family seeking a\nmoderate-priced home in a subur\nban atmosphere, this detached\nhouSe. located on a lot 42% feet\nwide and 132 feet deep, contains\nmany features of interest to the\nprospective home owner. A cloak\ncloset is just off the entrance\nhall and connects with the\nkitchen, which is in turn joined\nby a breakfast nook opening on\nto the rear porch. The living\nroom, with its large open fire\nplace and ample wall space, ad\njoins the dining room through a\ndouble doorwav. French doors\nopen off the dining room to a\nlarge porch.\nA light, airy basement, run\nning the full depth of the house,\ncontains built-in tubs, hot water\nheater, furnace and coal bins. A\nrear door leads to a well con\nstructed garage at the rear of\nthe property.\nThe ground surrounding the\nhouse has been beautifully sodded\nand, attractively landscaped with\nshrubs and flowers.\nTo visit this attractive home in\nBayard Park neighborhood, go\nnorth on Wisconsin Avenue to\nBrandywine Street and west to\nhome on Forty-fourth Street.\nHoumlnx worries orrer confront a\nhome-owarr\u2014abolish these worries for\nlife through the purchase of one of the\nhomes advertised for sale In today\u2019s\nClassified Ads.\nBlock Letter Signs Urged\nFor Aviation Guidance\nRoadside sign posts direct only\na.part of the inland travel to\nday. Large signs on roofs tell air\ntravelers the name of the town\nbelow them, pointgout the nearest\nairports and give the directions of\nthe compass. At night the signs\nare illuminated and. like light\nhouses to guide steamships, can\nbe seen by pilots miles away.\nWith the phenominal growth of\naviation in the last three years\nsince Colonel Lindbergh\u2019s flight\nto Paris, the need for these signs\nis apparent. The number of\nplanes in use has multiplied many'\ntimes. A network of air lines in\nterlaces the country. Hangars,\nairports, airplane factories have\nsprung up on all sides. Airplane\nshow rooms, aviation schools and\nand aviation country clubs are\nnot uncommon sights.\nProminent Situation\n.The roof for the air sign is us\nually chosen for its prominent\nsituation.\nBuildings near railroad stations\nhave been found desirable for the\nreason that pilots, especially when\nlost and seeking for bearing, fol\nlow railroad lines.\nA roof covered with smoke from\ntrain yards or factories, however,\nis not preferred since the smoke\nmakes the sign more difficult to\nread.\nIf there are two or more rail\nroad lines entering a town it is\nbest to have signs near each. In\nany case, the value of the work\nis increased if more than one\nbuilding is chosen.\nThe roof selected is preferably\nof tile, shingle, metal. or slate\nwith the sign painted directly on\nthe roof material. Roofs of gravel\ntop and of asphalt have been\nused advantageously by con\n17th Street N. W.\nAn Uptown Apartment Haute\nWhere It It Pottible to Ob\ntain Comfort, Service anti\nModerate Rent alt.\nI 1-rootn \u00bbnir\u00abment and bath\n130 monthly\n1-rm kitchenette and bath anta.\n<50.00\n1 rm. kitchenette bath apt., (45.00\n1 large S-rootn apt. with western,\ntotem <nd southern exooiurea.\nMO monthly\nTheaa apartments are unfurnished,\nnewly decorated and most attractive\nin every way.\nCALL AND INSPECT\nB. FERSINGEK, Resident Manager\nNorth cne\nfOR T BA RD PARK\nWASHINGTON NEW COMMUNITY OT EARLY AMERICAN HOME\nIBS\nJJ WirffT\n0\nBill\n:TOwBSrfcOKJf7 IL\u2019\u2019 \u2022\u00a3T\nNew Detached Colonial Homes\n1 n <-n Built and Equipped in the Manner\n1U,40U o f p ar ore E X p ens i ve Homes\ntoOITUATED in picturesque St. Ann\u2019s Parish, that\nbeautiful section just west of Wisconsin Avenue\n<-d z\\ AEf A (the Lincoln Highway)\u2014the ideal place for a home\nlUst/Ov where children can play ih absolute safety. There is a\nfine new public school and stores near enough to Fort\nBayard Park to be convenient, while churches of\nEaty Terms May various denominations are nearby. You must see\nBe Arranged these homes which offer such extraordinary value.\nEIGHT SOLD\nThree big porches four rooms and generous hall on first\nrjnvv floor han< some Colonial brick fireplace radio aerials in\nVzx JEiIN attic %-inch oak floors and stairways behutiful tiled bath\nexpensively equipped two-part laundry trays storage\nEVERY DAY automatic gas water heaters kitchen attractive in appear-\nance, scientific in design, up-to-minqte, with labor-saving con-\n9 A If in Q P M veniences unusually attractive garages to match .t. large\nA. Wl. 10 \u00ab7 a IVI. 1 lot, entirely sodded and finely landscaped.\nGo North on Wisconsin Ave. to Brandywine St. and West on\nBrandywine to 44th St. Less Than 15 Minutes to City.\nRQSSStPHEI PC\n1417 K St. Founded iht National 9300\nOWNERS\n1 5 l\nGet Our Large Rent List\nThe High Elevation .of Fort Bayard Park Always Assures Cool Breezes.\n\nAD VFRTISIN u\nstructing wooden letters and rais\ning them above roof level.\nSimple Block Letters\nA simple block letter in chrome\nyellow with a dark background\nis generally used. Uncolored\nwhite lead paint may be used,\nbut the addition of chrome pig\nrrient to the paint increases\nsomewhat the legibility of the\nsign. Letters less than six feet\nin size are of little value. Ten\nto twenty-foot letters make the\nmost readable signs. Clear ab\nbreviations of the name in large\nletters are preferred to the full\nname painted in small letters.\nj\u00dfeside the name of the town\nor city, the marking should in\nclude a large arrow pointing due\nnortir with the letter \u201cN\u201d under\nor over the arrow shaft.\nBuilding Permits\nBuilding permits issued for the\npast week amounted to $131,748\nand are as follows:\nCharle\u00df D. Sager. <so,ooo\u2014To erect\nJO two-etory brick dwellings at 515 to\n536 Twenty-third St. N. E. Lot 101-\n110. square 4516.\nRuth Hanna McCormick, <21.000 \u2014To\nbuild one bathhouse and one conserva\ntory In rear of dwelfing at 1224 Thir\ntieth St. N. W.\nFrank L. Fanning. <l4.ooo\u2014To ere<t\none two-story brick and tiam\u00ab dwell\ning at 1545 Alaska Ave. JC. W. Lot\n59. square 2955.\nLeo .1. Mansing. <ll,soo\u2014To erect one\none-story stone and brick gasoline\nservice station at 4401 Coanocticut Ave.\nN. W.\nM. and R. B. Warren, <4.soo\u2014Tn\nerect one two-story brick and stucco\ndwelling at 3040 Porter St. N. W. Lot\n104-105. square 2067.\nProtestant Episcopal Cathedral of\nDistrict of Columbia, <4.300 I\u2019o make\nrepairss to structure at Wisconsin Ave.\nand Woodley Rd.\nLewis Hotel Training School, <2,673\n\u2014To make interior repairs to structure\nat 1001-03-05 Twenty-third St N. W.\nInvest In home-ownership through\nthe Real Estate for Sale columns of\ntoday's Classified Ads.\nPLUM POINT BEACH\nDelightful Salt Water Bathing at\nChesapeake\u2019s Finest Beach\nFine Shade, Pure Artesian Water\nK Home sites on gently rolling hills with view of bay,\nand with beach privileges, at pre-development prices.\n\u2022\u25a0.A\u2019c.\nPLUM POINT BEACH\ni 1125 14th St. N.W.\nPhone National 2034\nREALIORS PLUS\nmiisiNCi\nSERVICE 3\nA plan whereby individual\nrealtors can be given an advertis\ning service through the National\nAssociation of Real Estate Boards\nwas approved at the Toronto con\nvention of that organization by\nthe association\u2019s board of dila\ntors, and will be put in operation\nif and when 100 constituent\nboards of the association indicate\ntheir desire to use the proposed\nservice.\nAt the Toronto meeting, W\nboards at once pledged themselvs\nto the use of such a bureau. The\nplan was developed in response tb\nrequests of the association*\nboards everywhere for professional\nhelp in real estate advertising app\nthe program outlined for the'\nservice is viewed as one of tlj\u00df\nlargest undertakings which the\nassociation has ever proposed for\nimmediate service to the indi\nvidual realtor.\nThe proposal for advertising\nservice was brought before the\nboard of directors by Hugh Pottef.\nHouston. Tex., chairman of the\nnational association\u2019s special eum\nmittee which has been engaged\nfor the past six months in develop\ning a plan for an advisory bureap\nIn approving Mr. Potter\u2019s rdjk\nommendation, the board of direc\ntors approved the proposal of Her\nbert U. Nelson, executive secijj\ntary of the National Association\nof Real Estate Boards, that if and\nwhen 100 member boards of the\nassociation sponsored the plan an\nadvisory advertising bureau wffl\nbe established at national head\nquarters. 7","height":"30488","width":"24468"}}
